04290nam a22006615i 9780231544795DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021036400  a97802315447957 a10.7312/finc183202doi  a(DE-B1597)627188  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC481b.F5179 2022 4aJC481 7aPOL0420302bisacsh04a320.53/3223/eng/202112021 aFinchelstein, Federico, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFascist Mythologies :bThe History and Politics of Unreason in Borges, Freud, and Schmitt /cFederico Finchelstein. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory ;v7900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Myth and Fascism -- t2 Freud, Fascism, and the Return of the Myth -- t3 Borges and Fascism as Mythology -- t4 Borges and the Persistence of Myth -- t5 A Fascist History Carl Schmitt’s Political Theory of Myth -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor fascism, myth was reality—or was realer than the real. Fascist notions of the leader, the nation, power, and violence were steeped in mythic imagery and the fantasy of transcending history. A mythologized primordial past would inspire the heroic overthrow of a debased present to achieve a violently redeemed future. What is distinctive about fascist mythology, and how does this aspect of fascism help explain its perils in the past and present?Federico Finchelstein draws on a striking combination of thinkers—Jorge Luis Borges, Sigmund Freud, and Carl Schmitt—to consider fascism as a form of political mythmaking. He shows that Borges’s literary and critical work and Freud’s psychoanalytic writing both emphasize the mythical and unconscious dimensions of fascist politics. Finchelstein considers their ideas of the self, violence, and the sacred as well as the relationship between the victims of fascist violence and the ideological myths of its perpetrators. He draws on Freud and Borges to analyze the work of a variety of Latin American and European fascist intellectuals, with particular attention to Schmitt’s political theology. Contrasting their approaches to the logic of unreason, Finchelstein probes the limits of the dichotomy between myth and reason and shows the centrality of this opposition to understanding the ideology of fascism.At a moment when forces redolent of fascism cast a shadow over world affairs, this book provides a timely historical and critical analysis of the dangers of myth in modern politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aFascism. 0aMythxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Fascism & Totalitarianism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/finc1832040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231544795/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK